m, Kent, England":"Lenham, Kent, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Royton, Lenham, Kent, England":"Lenham, Kent, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","St Mary's Church, Lenham, Kent, England":"Lenham, Kent, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Royton, Lancashire, England":"Royton, Lancashire, England"},"en":{"1392–1467":"1392–1467","1390–1481":"1390–1481","1409–1484":"1409–1484","1467":"1467","1484":"1484","1409":"1409","1481":"1481","1392":"1392","1408":"1408","1390":"1390","Lenham, Kent, England":"Lenham, Kent, England, United Kingdom","Royton, Lenham, Kent, England":"Lenham, Kent, England, United Kingdom","St Mary's Church, Lenham, Kent, England":"Lenham, Kent, England, United Kingdom","Royton, Lancashire, England":"Royton, Lancashire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Marr","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish: habitational name from the district of Mar in Aberdeenshire, an ancient tribal name probably based on a Brittonic personal name <i>Marsos</i>. There may have been confusion with   Mair   2.","English: habitational name from one or other of various places called from Old Norse <i>marr</i> ‘fen, marsh’, such as Marr, High and Low Marr in Wheldrake, and The Marrs in Swine (all Yorkshire).","German: from the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Marro</i>."],"variants":[{"name":"Marrs","meanings":["English: variant of   Marr  , with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>."]},{"name":"Morr","meanings":["Perhaps an altered form of German   Marr   3."]},{"name":"Mair","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Franz, Alois, Benno, Egon, Hans, Hermann, Inge, Kurt, Othmar, Otto, Reinhard, Rudi.","Scottish: variant of   Marr   1.","Scottish: occupational name from Gaelic <i>maor</i> ‘officer’, used specifically for an officer who executed summonses and other legal writs, including not only the king's herald or sergeant but also head foresters and the like. See also   Maver   and compare   Mayer   3."]}]},{"name":"Joan","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Contracted form of Old French <i>Jo(h)anne</i>, from Latin <i>Io(h)anna</i> (  see  Joanna  ). In England this was the usual feminine form of   John   from the Middle English period onwards and was extremely popular, but in the 16th and 17th centuries it steadily lost ground to   Jane .  It was strongly revived in the first part of the 20th century, partly under the influence of  George Bernard Shaw's  play St Joan (  1923 ), based on the life of  Joan of Arc  (  1412–31 ). Claiming to be guided by the voices of the saints, she persuaded the French dauphin to defy the occupying English forces and have himself crowned, and she led the French army that raised the siege of Orleans in  1429 . The following year she was captured by the Burgundians and sold to the English, and a year later she was burned at the stake for witchcraft at the age of 18 or 19. Her story has captured the imagination of many writers, and she is variously portrayed as a national and political hero, a model of apolitical straightforwardness and honesty, and a religious heroine. She was canonized in  1920 . More recent influences have included the American film actress  Joan Crawford  (  1908–77 , born  Lucille le Sueur ), the British actress  Joan Collins  (  b. 1933 ), the American comedienne  Joan Rivers  (  b. 1933 ), and the West Indian pop singer  Joan Armatrading  (  b. 1950 )."],"variants":[{"name":"John","meanings":["Greek: the Lord gave graciously; whom Jehovah gave; whom Jehovah bestowed."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Joan Marr was born in 1392, in Lenham, Kent, England, United Kingdom. She married John Atwater in 1408, in Lenham, Kent, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died in 1467, in her hometown, at the age of 75, and was buried in Lenham, Kent, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1392–1467":"1392–1467","1390–1481":"13